= lesson 26: love and identity

You've already seen that #strong[ůĪ§ßůĪ•ĒůĪ•©ůĪ§ī ... li pona tawa mi] is a common way to
say '#emph[i like ...]'. And, of course, we can say #strong[ůĪ•ĒůĪ§ľ pona mute] to
talk about #emph[really liking] someone. But that's not the same as
#emph[loving] someone! So let's look at words for love, and what to call people
you love:

#list((
  word("ůĪ•Ö", "olin", "to love"),
  word("ůĪ•Į", "unpa", "to have sex"),
  word("ůĪ§Ī", "mama", "parent"),
  word("ůĪ§Ķ", "mije", "man, masculine person, husband; male"),
  word("ůĪ§≥", "meli", "woman, feminine person, wife; female"),
  word("ůĪ•ĺ", "tonsi", "non-binary, gender-nonconforming; trans"),
))

Many language courses start with words for "man, woman, girl, boy, mother,
father" and so on. In Toki Pona, gender is not so important. You won't see
#strong[ůĪ§Ķ mije], #strong[ůĪ§≥ meli], #strong[ůĪ•ĺ tonsi] in every sentence. They
mostly come up when talking about social expectations about gender, and
relationships in particular.

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ•ÖůĪ§ČůĪ§ĶůĪ§ī", "mi olin e mije mi.", "I love my boyfriend."),
  sentence("ůĪ§ĪůĪ•Ą", "mama o!", "Mom! (or) Dad!"),
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ•ÖůĪ§ČůĪ§≥", "mi olin e meli.", "I'm into girls."),
))

The word 'non-binary' comes from recent Western culture, but an identity that is
separate from men and women exists in many other cultures from different times,
like Scythian #link("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enaree")[enarei], Samoan
#link("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa%CA%BBafafine")[fa'afafine], Thai #link(
  "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathoey",
)[kathoey], and so on. #strong[ůĪ•ĺ tonsi] is a word to describe any of them, it
doesn't imply any particular culture.

Some more examples of situations where gender could be relevant:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ§•ůĪ§īůĪ§ßůĪ§Ķ", "len mi li mije.", "I dress masculine."),
  sentence("ůĪ§ĎůĪ•ÖůĪ§īůĪ§ßůĪ•ĺ", "jan olin mi li tonsi.", "My partner is non-binary."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§īůĪ§≥ůĪ§ČůĪ•õůĪ§īůĪ§ôůĪ¶á",
    "mi meli e sijelo mi kepeken misikeke.",
    "I make my body more feminine with medication.",
  ),
))

== multiple subjects

We've already seen how #emph['e ... e ...'] can be used to introduce several
objects to the sentence, and how #emph['li ... li ...'] can be used to introduce
several verbs. But we can't just put two subjects next to each other, because
you wouldn't know where one subject ends and another begins. To solve this
problem, we use a new particle in between:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§ä", "en", "joins subjects"),
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ§äůĪ•ÜůĪ§ßůĪ•¨", "mi en ona li toki.", "Me and her are chatting."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•ĘůĪ§äůĪ•īůĪ§ßůĪ•Ī",
    "soweli en waso li utala.",
    "The animal and the bird are fighting.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§≥ůĪ§äůĪ§ĶůĪ§ßůĪ•Į",
    "meli en mije li unpa.",
    "The woman and the man have sex.",
  ),
))

